    "excerpt": "How one artist turned a stadium tour into a cultural phenomenon — by the numbers.",
    "body": "When the tour was announced eighteen months ago, industry observers were cautiously optimistic. When it concluded last month, it had grossed $2.2 billion — making it the highest-earning concert tour in history.\n\nThe numbers are staggering. 124 shows across 42 countries. Over 8 million tickets sold. An average attendance of 65,000 per show. A merchandise operation that generated more revenue than some entire record labels.\n\nThe stage design alone took three years to develop, involving engineers from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory. The result was a 360-degree performance space that could be assembled in under twelve hours.\n\n'The goal was to create something that couldn't be replicated on a screen,' the tour's creative director told us. 'We wanted every person in that stadium to feel like they were the only person in the stadium.'\n\nTicket pricing was deliberately accessible, with the cheapest seats starting at $49 — significantly below market rate.",
