    "title": "Streaming Wars: Which Platform Dominated the Summer Ratings?",
    "excerpt": "A data-driven breakdown of viewership, subscriber growth, and breakout hits.",
    "body": "The summer of 2026 has been the most competitive period in streaming history. Six major platforms released original programming at a rate that made weekly viewing schedules nearly impossible to track.\n\nThe numbers tell a clear story. Platform A led in total viewership hours, driven by the return of its flagship drama series. Platform B led in subscriber growth, adding 12 million new accounts.\n\nPlatform C had the most critically acclaimed programming, with three of the top five highest-rated series of the summer. Platform D won the documentary race with a true-crime series that dominated social media.\n\nThe most interesting trend was about the audience. The average subscriber now maintains 3.4 active streaming subscriptions — up from 2.8 last year.\n\n'The streaming wars are over,' one analyst told us. 'What we're seeing now is the streaming equilibrium.'",
